Prior to the decolonization, a large number of British nationals lived in Antigua and Barbuda, and after independence of a few important social and commercial roles have been taken over by British companies. Most of these companies moved to the Caribbean free port immediately. The removal of a part of the administrative forces together with increasing popular support for de Beers company’s diamond mine in St. Johns, the inequality of development has become more significant for comparative development of the country, which has relegated its economy.

After Antigua and Barbuda becoming an independent state in 1981, it continued handling its external trade with the former colonial power until 1992, while the payment of debt’s received from the British government during the colonial period became the focus of discussions. Accordingly, an external debt amounting to approximately 72 million U.S. dollars was cancelled. While the government has been worried about the increase in the debt of a total of 90 million U.S. dollars since 1994, it has proven the debt securitization arrangement. According to this arrangement, the country was able to reduce the annual debt payments required from 8.7 million U.S. dollars it had to 1 million U.S. dollars.
